article.headline: Creighton 74, Oregon State 64
article.story:
OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Oregon State was the only team in the WNIT
quarterfinals that didn't have the luxury of at least two full days
off between games.

Creighton (22-9) took full advantage in a 74-64 win on
Wednesday, advancing to the semifinals for the second year in a
row.

"We just try to wear all our opponents down," said Dayna
Finch, who finished with a game-high 22 points and eight rebounds.
"When they get tired they take tougher shots. I think that's the
key to all of our games. I think our intensity was a little bit
better and we just wanted to win."

The Bluejays' up-tempo game finally wore down the Beavers by
holding them to only 29 percent shooting from the floor in the
final 20 minutes.

"I thought we contested shots a better and took care of the
ball," Creighton coach Jim Flanery said. "They had kids who
played major minutes on Monday and to come back two nights later
against a team that's going to press you for 40 minutes, you kind
of assume that's going to affect your shooting percentage."

Finch's fourth 3-pointer of the game started the Bluejays' big
push at the 6:24 mark, breaking a 54-54 tie.

Laura Spanheimer's three-point play with 3:57 remaining
concluded the run and gave the Bluejays a 63-55 advantage.

Before that rally, Creighton's biggest lead was four points.

There were 14 ties and 11 lead changes in the tight matchup.

Oregon State (17-15) was led by senior forward Hollye Chapman
who scored 18 points and grabbed 12 rebounds. Brina Chaney added 11
points for the Beavers.

Despite shooting only 35.7 percent in the first half, Creighton
went into the locker room at halftime tied at 35.

Oregon State held the Bluejays scoreless for four minutes in the
first half and went on a 10-2 run to build its biggest lead of 16-9
with 12:06 to play but never again took a big lead.

"We just didn't have our legs," Oregon State coach Judy
Spoelstra said. "We were the only team that didn't have an extra
day off and you can just tell it really showed. That second half we
were just stuck in a rut."

Christy Neneman scored 15 and Angie Janis added 12 for
Creighton.

The Bluejays next face Richmond when they play host at 1 p.m.
Saturday.
